[49m[38;5;9m- 527     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Score versioning and comparability.** If you retrain your risk model (which you should, periodically), the new model's scores are not directly comparable to the old model's scores. A patient whose score went from 0.3 to 0.5 might have genuinely deteriorated, or the new model might just score everyone higher. Production systems need either: (a) re-score the full history with the new model whenever you retrain, or (b) maintain version-specific percentile baselines and compare within-version only. Both approaches have tradeoffs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Score versioning and comparability.** If you retrain your risk model (which you should, periodically), the new model's scores are not directly comparable to the old model's scores. A patient whose score went from 0.3 to 0.5 might have genuinely deteriorated, or the new model might just score everyone higher. Production systems need either: (a) re-score the full history with the new model whenever you retrain, or (b) maintain version-specific percentile baselines and compare within-version only. Both approaches have tradeoffs. For most organizations, option (b) is more practical: after a model retrain, accept a reduced trajectory window until enough new-version scores accumulate. Design your minimum data point threshold (currently 3) to account for this reset.
